  "slug": "plum-frangipane-tart",
  "title": "Plum frangipane tart",
  "subtitle": "Quartered plums on almond cream in a sweet shortcrust",
  "excerpt": "Autumn plums quartered and pressed cut-side up into almond frangipane in a sweet shortcrust shell. The plums weep their juice into the frangipane and turn deep purple in the bake. One 23 cm tart, serving eight.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Eliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845), Project Gutenberg: documents the British plum-frangipane tart in the autumn-fruit section. Marie-Antoine Carême, L'Art de la cuisine française (1833), Project Gutenberg: documents the French frangipane form. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: documents the use of stone fruit pressed into almond cream as a household tart shape.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A plum frangipane tart has three layers. First a blind-baked sweet shortcrust shell. Then a frangipane filling, which is an almond cream made of butter, sugar, eggs, ground almonds and a little flour. Then quartered plums pressed cut-side up into the cream before it goes in the oven. The plums sink slightly into the cream and stain it with their juice. The surface darkens to deep gold as the tart bakes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Victoria plums, damsons, mirabelles and Marjorie's Seedlings all work; small plums halved, larger plums quartered. Damsons need an extra teaspoon of sugar in the frangipane; mirabelles and Victorias usually do not.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
